  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What books could I use to teach myself math from the ground up?",
  "response": "Teaching yourself math from the ground up is a great endeavor, and there are numerous books that can guide you through the fundamentals to more advanced topics. Here are some recommendations:\n\n### Basic Arithmetic and Pre-Algebra:\n1. **\"Prealgebra\" by Richard Rusczyk** - This book covers the fundamentals of arithmetic and introduces basic algebraic concepts.\n2. **\"Basic Mathematics\" by Serge Lang** - A comprehensive introduction to fundamental mathematical concepts, suitable for beginners.\n\n### Algebra:\n1. **\"Algebra: Structure and Method, Book 1\" by Richard G. Brown** - This classic textbook provides a thorough introduction to algebraic principles.\n2. **\"Algebra\" by Israel M. Gelfand and Alexander Shen** - A concise and clear introduction to algebra.\n\n### Geometry:\n1. **\"Geometry: Seeing, Doing, Understanding\" by Harold R. Jacobs** - An engaging and comprehensive introduction to geometry.\n2. **\"Euclidean and Non-Euclidean Geometries: Development and History\" by Marvin Jay Greenberg** - This book provides a historical perspective on geometry.\n\n### Trigonometry:\n1. **\"Trigonometry\" by I.M. Gelfand** - A concise and accessible introduction to trigonometric concepts.\n2. **\"Trigonometry\" by Cynthia Y. Young** - A more detailed textbook with plenty of practice problems.\n\n### Calculus:\n1. **\"Calculus\" by Michael Spivak** - A rigorous and detailed introduction to calculus.\n2. **\"Calculus\" by James Stewart** - A widely-used textbook that covers the fundamentals and provides extensive practice problems.\n\n### Linear Algebra:\n1. **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler** - A clear and conceptual introduction to linear algebra.\n2. **\"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Gilbert Strang** - Comprehensive and accessible, with applications in various fields.\n\n### Probability and Statistics:\n1. **\"Introduction to the Theory of Statistics\" by Alexander Mood, Franklin Graybill, and Duane Boes** - A thorough introduction to probability and statistics.\n2. **\"Statistics\" by Robert S. Witte and John S. Witte** - A detailed and practical approach to statistical concepts.\n\n### Discrete Mathematics:\n1. **\"Discrete Mathematics and Its Applications\" by Kenneth H. Rosen** - Covers a broad range of topics in discrete mathematics.\n2. **\"Concrete Mathematics: A Foundation for Computer Science\" by Ronald Graham, Donald Knuth, and Oren Patashnik** - A more advanced book with a focus on applications in computer science.\n\n### Additional Resources:\n- **\"How to Solve It\" by George Polya** - A classic book on problem-solving techniques in mathematics.\n- **\"What is Mathematics?\" by Richard Courant and Herbert Robbins** - A broad overview of various mathematical topics, suitable for self-study.\n\n### Online Resources:\n- **Khan Academy** - Provides free instructional videos and practice exercises on a wide range of mathematical topics.\n- **MIT OpenCourseWare** - Offers free course materials from MIT, including lecture notes, assignments, and exams for various math courses.\n\nWhen selecting books, consider your current level and progress gradually. Mathematics builds on itself, so a solid understanding of the basics will make advanced topics easier to tackle.",
